
> Top-Line Performance: The company's revenue declined over the past four years. Net sales decreased to $1,209.4m in FY25 from $1,386.4m in FY24, representing a 12.8% YoY decline of $177.4m. The decline was driven by lower e-commerce sales due to lower traffic and conversion and lower brick-and-mortar revenue from reduced traffic, particularly in the first half of the year, with both channels impaired by the macroeconomic environment and tariffs negatively affecting the target consumer. Comparable retail sales declined 8.4% for the full year and 10.7% in Q4, with Q4 net sales contracting 19.4% to $329.2m from $408.6m. Store count closed at 498 vs 510 at FY24 year-end.

> Profitability: The company's profitability deteriorated materially over FY25. Gross margin declined to 29.9% in FY25 from 33.1% in FY24, down 320 basis points, caused primarily by an increase in inventory reserves (200 bps), the impact of higher tariffs on the Company's product (140 bps), and higher penetration of markdowns and dilutions; Q4 FY25 gross margin contracted ~500 bps to 23.5%. Operating margin deteriorated to ~(4.7)% in FY25 from ~(1.0)% in FY24, with operating loss widening to ~$(57.2)m from $(13.7)m in FY24, driven by gross margin compression, tariff impact ($15-$20m for FY25), and SG&A deleverage; Q4 FY25 alone produced an operating loss of $(40.9)m vs operating income of $6.8m in Q4 FY24, deleveraging 1,410 basis points to (12.4)% of net sales. Net loss widened to $(88.3)m, or $(4.01) per diluted share, in FY25 from $(57.8)m or $(4.53) per diluted share in FY24, with adjusted net loss of $(81.4)m, or $(3.70) per diluted share, compared with adjusted net income of $5.5m, or $0.43 per diluted share, in FY24, reflecting the combined effect of gross margin compression, operating deleverage, and lower contribution from prior-year non-recurring tax benefits.

> Cash Flows: In FY25, operating cash flow was $8.1m, compared with $(117.6)m in FY24, reflecting an improvement of $125.7m. The improvement was driven by working capital management with a reduction in inventory balances of $74.5 million compared to the prior year; the swing is mechanical (inventory destocking) rather than profitability-driven, as net loss widened by ~$30m in the same period.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of January 31, 2026, cash and cash equivalents totalled $5.5m, with $44.4m of revolver availability and $40.0m of unsecured availability under the Mithaq Commitment Letter, representing total liquidity of $89.9m, against $131.1m outstanding on the revolving credit facility (Mithaq commitment undrawn). Capital structure was reset during FY25 via a $450m refinancing package ($350m ABL plus $100m FILO term loan), replacing the prior Wells Fargo facility. Total debt consists primarily of the refinanced ABL plus related-party Mithaq term loans, with $18.4m outstanding under the Initial Mithaq Term Loan ($78.6m original, $60.2m repaid via the February 2025 rights offering) maturing February 15, 2027; the Company carried a stockholders' deficit of $(54.2)m at year-end.

> Working Capital: Working capital improved through aggressive destocking but remained constrained in FY25. Inventories declined to $325.1 million as of January 31, 2026, compared to $399.6 million as of February 1, 2025, a $74.5m or 18.6% reduction. Days inventory outstanding (derived) declined to ~140 days in FY25 from ~157 days in FY24, with the CCC narrowing correspondingly; further inventory cushion is limited going into FY26 tariff escalation ($25-$30m H1 impact guided).

> Operational Restructuring Plan: Effective February 2026, the Company migrated to the Salesforce Customer Cloud platform to stabilise the customer file and drive increased traffic through faster execution, sharper segmentation, and a superior customer experience; in parallel, store footprint rationalisation continued (498 stores vs 510 PY). The Company announced a strategic partnership with Al Othaim on April 27, 2026 to re-enter the Saudi Arabian market, providing a Mithaq-aligned regional growth pathway, alongside ongoing cost reduction, margin expansion, and free cash flow prioritisation under the FY26 transformation agenda.

> Going Concern: The FY25 audit opinion does not include an explicit "substantial doubt" statement; however, the 10-K's risk-factor language explicitly contemplates that historical operating losses, macroeconomic uncertainties, volatility in financial markets, and US retail credit-portfolio losses are factors that may impair the Company's ability to finance operations or refinance the ABL Credit Facility or other outstanding indebtedness. Combined with negative shareholders' equity of $(54.2)m, four consecutive years of revenue contraction, and total liquidity dependent on a $40m unsecured commitment letter from the controlling shareholder, the underlying signals are restructuring-adjacent.

> Securities Litigation Overhang: On February 19, 2026 (reiterated April 13, 2026), Johnson Fistel, PLLP announced an investigation of potential claims on behalf of investors of The Children's Place, focused on whether public statements concerning inventory reserves complied with federal securities laws. The investigation aligns with three consecutive quarters of material inventory-reserve hits to gross margin (Q3 FY25: 240 bps; Q4 FY25: 160 bps; FY25: 200 bps), creating restatement and settlement-cash-drain risk in parallel to the operational turnaround.

> Management Change: Effective November 20, 2025, the Board of Directors removed the "interim" designation from Muhammad Umair's role and appointed him as permanent President and Chief Executive Officer (he had served as Interim CEO since 2024); Turki S. AlRajhi continues as Executive Chairman, authoring annual letters to shareholders. During Fiscal 2024, Mithaq Capital SPC (a Cayman segregated portfolio company) acquired more than 50% of the Company's outstanding common stock and became the controlling stockholder; during Fiscal 2025, Mithaq further increased its shareholding via the rights offering, taking voting control to 62%; the governance transition was formalised March 8, 2024. Additional senior leadership appointments were announced February 24, 2026: Kim Roy as Executive Director and Lisa Pillette as Chief Customer Officer, effective March 2, 2026.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. The Form 10-K for the fiscal year ended January 31, 2026 was filed on April 10, 2026 within the statutory deadline, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported. Reporting controls remain intact despite the underlying operating and balance-sheet stress.
